# Simplify

## The Baseline Rules
- Don't add features, refactors, or abstractions beyond what the task requires
- Don't design for hypothetical future requirements
- Three similar lines is better than a premature abstraction
- No half-finished implementations — ship it or don't write it

## Error Handling
- Only validate at system boundaries: user form input and external API responses
- Trust React's guarantees, TypeScript types, and internal component contracts
- Don't add fallback states for scenarios the code prevents from happening

## Comments
- Default: zero comments
- Only add a comment when the WHY is non-obvious — a browser quirk, a hidden constraint, a workaround
- Never write JSDoc blocks or multi-line comment explanations of what the code does

## Components & Abstractions
- Don't extract a helper used in only one place
- Don't split a component unless the file exceeds ~400 lines or the piece is reused 3+ times
- Don't add loading states unless there is a real async operation (avoid skeleton shimmer theater)

## Inline Styles
- Keep styles co-located with the element they affect (status quo in this project)
- Don't prematurely extract a shared style object unless it's used in 3+ places in the same file
- Don't introduce a CSS-in-JS library or theme system — the project intentionally avoids this

## What "Done" Means
- The feature works at 375 px, 768 px, and 1280 px
- `npm run check` passes (TypeScript)
- `npm run lint` passes
- No console errors or warnings in the browser
